Has a very nice bore for being made in 1919 and having been used with black powder 22 rounds earlier in its life. Has shine left in it and not all pitted up. Wood has some fine hairling cracks up fore end but nothing bad and nothing through all the way. Blue is wore down to a nice patina in spots but no pitting on metal. Very collectible and in great shape wincehster 1902 rifle. Barrel reads 02 instead of 1902 first year for that was 1919 and after that it changed with different spacing. Also is in short, long and extral long 22 caliber. All rollmarks very nice and legible.

title: For Sale:  DSA RPD RPDS NIB California NY NJ
postcontent:
What catches our attention more than a belt fed rifle? Be honest. Haven't you dreamed of owning a belt fed machine-gun lookalike? No? Quick! Check your pulse. You're dead! I get excited just hefting this beauty. I've always liked these. I've had them on backorder with my distributor since August of 2011. They finally arrived and it was worth the wait. These rifles are beautiful! I'm referring to the DSArms brand new in the box RPDS belt fed in 7.62X39. These were assembled by DSA using one of their own semi-auto receivers and, I believe, excellent condition Polish parts sets. The rifles are factory new. The furniture may have dings from their previous life. Some of the metal might too. Everything has been refinished and is beautiful. You can confirm that in the photos. The RPD was one in a series of weapons by a Russian arms designer named Degtyarov. Many of you will recognize that name. What he means most to me is the robust and simple locking system that he developed in the DP and continued on through the RPD to the PKM and even the big DSHK. In the RPD, due to its smaller caliber, the action is remarkable robust. The machinegun was put into widescale service in 1953. It was the standard machine gun of the Vietcong during our war with them. Once the Kalashnikov guns came into favor, Russia moved away from the RPD, but it continues to serve in African and Asian nations right up until today. I think I read that Bolivia still uses them too. So, although this is a design of an earlier time, it's effective enough to still serve in smaller countries today. It has this proven heritage. These guns fire from the closed bolt using a striker. The semi-auto disconnect limits them to one round per trigger pull. Let me go over some features as I examine this trophy lying across my lap. The feed cover latches positively and locks open reliably. Lifting it reveals a simple feed mechanism operated by the lug on the top rear of the bolt assembly. The rear sight is windage adjustable and has steps in 100 meter increments to 1000 meters. It has a square notch. I wonder how ballistically effective the AK round is out that far. Remember, it's ballistically about like a 30/30. The front handguard is wood. Pretty too. Moving forward is the block with the sling attachment point. Then comes the adjustable gas block. The front sight can be adjusted for windage and elevation to allow you to zero the rear sight. A bipod is mounted just to the rear of the front sight assembly. The bipod folds under the barrel. There is a cleaning rod to the lower left of the receiver. The feed mechanism has dust covers on both sides. There is a mechanism for hanging the belt drum which is a container for the non-disintegrating belt. The trigger pull is heavy. The safety is accessible to the right trigger finger. The wood buttstock is pristine. The buttplate has an access door to the recoil assembly and the cleaning kit storage. This rifle comes with two drums with belts and two canvas pouches to contain them. There is a canvas carry case for the rifle. There is a rifle sling, a cleaning and tool kit, an attachment that threads onto the muzzle to guide the cleaning rod and spare the muzzle. The rifle will arrive in an hard case. The manual is extensive. Very nice! I paid over $75 for my RPD manual and this one is every bit as good. I will be glad to do what's necessary to ship this to you in Alabama or other oppressive states. Do your homework to find out if your dealer will accept it and do the transfer, then email me before you bid and discuss what you need me to do. I am pleased to help fellow Americans legally obtain guns in spite of the unfriendly atmosphere in their home states. email is far too slow, text me 786-505-9474 
Asking $1.250 OBO

title: For Sale:  Noreen Bad News .338 Lapua ULR the Ultimate Semi-Automatic Sniper Rifle.
postcontent:
NOREEN BAD NEWS .338 Lapua !!!! 

Noreen has created the ONLY SEMI-AUTOMATIC .300 WIN MAG and .338 Lapua on the market. The BAD NEWS is a custom-made AR-style rifle that is chambered in the increasingly popular 338 Lapua as well as the powerful 300 WIN MAG. These cartridges give you much greater velocity and power than the typical .308, and as far as ballistics are concerned, the BAD NEWS rifle is going to be the flatter shooting gun for long range shots. 

The BAD NEWS rifle is a piston-driven semi-auto; this means you can expect greater range and a higher level of reliability by running a cleaner and cooler rifle. The muzzle break on these Noreen’s significantly suppresses recoil. Additionally, the semi-auto nature of the rifle will naturally recoil less than a bolt action because part of the felt recoil is going to chamber the next round. Lighter recoil is a huge advantage when you’re looking for a rifle with a faster and more accurate follow-up shot. 

This piston-driven system is unlike any other AR-10 on the market. The piston movement is strictly in the action, after the bullet has already left the barrel. This is a huge advantage on a precision rifle compared to conventional piston driven setups found in standard AR's. In those rifles, an LWRC REPR, POF P308, etc. the piston runs parallel to the barrel and moves while the bullet is still in the barrel creating unwanted barrel harmonics which adversely affect accuracy. This rifle's piston is located in the receiver and not along the barrel so the bullet is out of the barrel by the time the piston is working to chamber another round and keep your action cool and clean with no gas ever entering the action. 

The semi-automatic will not only give you a much faster follow-up shot, it also allows you to stay focused on your target, optic and the trigger, instead of having to manually operate a bolt-action rifle; all subsequent rounds are chambered by the rifle itself during the gas or blowback operation of the action. The innovative Noreen Bad News .338 Lapua ULR provides tactical marksmen with the performance of a powerful and proven long range cartridge with the numerous advantages of the venerable AR platform. This Noreen includes an ultra-heavy duty Plano case, which is far superior to a pelican style case. 100% Made in the USA and also includes, Piston-driven semi-automatic action

title: For Sale:  M91/30 Russian Mosin Nagant
postcontent: Russian M91/30 Mosin Nagant Rifle 7.62x54r caliber, 5 round Bolt Action.  Mother Russia's most historically proven early battle rifle and our most popular selling rifle by far.  And why not, these fine rifles have been meticulously refinished in Russian arsenals before release for export and they look great.  Not only are they 100% functional, but they have a reputation for being reliable, hard hitting, and extremely accurate.  The 7.62x54r round was the Warsaw Pact heavy caliber from the early 20's until modern day, so surplus ammunition is very plentiful and extremely affordable.  This renown cartridge is more powerful than a .308 and ballistically rivals our 30/06 caliber.  This round is more than adequate for harvesting any Big Game animal in North America.  Rifle is extremely accurate up to 300 plus yards with open sights and is capable of accuracy out to 1000 yards with proper optics.  Without a doubt the Mosin Nagant M91/30 provides by far the most bang for the buck of any rifle on the market today.  Here you have a rifle capable of taking any big game in North America at respectable yardage, fires affordable ammo, and can be obtained for less that the price of a high end pellet rifle.
